urls.title: Generative Code Camp Interest Form
urls.description: I've been teaching Generative Methods for many years now (https://www.mccormick.northwestern.edu/magazine/fall-2021/coding-brings-costumes-life/, https://github.com/galaxykate/GenerativeMethodsClass) and other classes where we use simple vanilla web tech to make games, social networks, costumes, and strange interactive toys, and take a tour of all of the "old-fashioned" tools for generating art with computers. I was thinking about offering an informal online summer tutorial (cuz plenty of us aren't in college), and wanted to gather interested emails now before Twitter goes down. And I'll let ya'll know when/if I kick it off! One way that I like to run this class is to have weekly assignments, usually with a lot of starter code, and then students can share their work on Glitch via a Discord. That allows a lot of creative collaboration and cross pollination of techniques, as well as a wee bit of accountability and socialization that is missing in traditional Watch My Video courses. And y

urls.title: VR Haptics at Home: Repurposing Everyday Objects and Environment for Casual and On-Demand VR Haptic Experiences | Extended Abstracts of the 2023 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems
urls.description: University of Calgary, Canada ATLAS Institute, University of Colorado Boulder, United States This paper introduces VR Haptics at Home, a method of repurposing everyday objects in the home to provide casual and on-demand haptic experiences. Current VR haptic devices are often expensive, complex, and unreliable, which limits the opportunities for rich haptic experiences outside research labs. In contrast, we envision that, by repurposing everyday objects as passive haptics props, we can create engaging VR
